&gt;&gt; The bumper sticker says, "Palin in 2012:
We'd love to kick your ass again." [laughs

01:10:40.880 --> 01:10:41.880
from audience] My question to you is more
about -

01:10:41.880 --> 01:10:42.880
John Heilemann: That's funny. You got the
kind of like Sarah Palin is going to be in

01:10:42.880 --> 01:10:43.880
this.

01:10:43.880 --> 01:10:44.880
&gt;&gt; I don't think she's really going to have
a chance in the primary but in the 2008 election,

01:10:44.880 --> 01:10:45.880
I wonder if you could just talk for a few
minutes about what happened in New Hampshire.

01:10:45.880 --> 01:10:46.880
All of the polls ahead of that primary had
shown that Barack Obama was going to win.

01:10:46.880 --> 01:10:47.880
He had come out of the Iowa caucuses with
a gold halo and nobody expected Hillary Clinton

01:10:47.880 --> 01:10:48.880
to take that particular primary. What do you
think actually happened there?

01:10:48.880 --> 01:10:49.880
John Heilemann: That's a good question and
I think I know the answer; that's what makes

01:10:49.880 --> 01:10:50.880
it an even better question. Where to start?
Mark Penn, Hillary Clinton's Chief Strategist,

01:10:50.880 --> 01:10:51.880
had a theory which was that a lot of - the
Clintons obviously have a strong connection

01:10:51.880 --> 01:10:52.880
to the state of New Hampshire that Obama never
had. Obama had done

01:10:52.880 --> 01:10:53.880
a lot of work in Iowa, the Clintons had never
had a history there. The difference between

01:10:53.880 --> 01:10:54.880
the states go largely to that. But the Clintons
had a strong reservoir of support in New Hampshire

01:10:54.880 --> 01:10:55.880
and that was the first important thing. Second
important thing was that there were a lot

01:10:55.880 --> 01:10:56.880
of woman voters in New Hampshire had, for
a variety of reasons, drifted away from Hillary

01:10:56.880 --> 01:10:57.880
Clinton and drifted largely not into Obama's
column but into the undecided column. So Mark

01:10:57.880 --> 01:10:58.880
Penn's theory was that Hillary Clinton needed
to get those, needed to reactivate those women

01:10:58.880 --> 01:10:59.880
voters who were inclined towards her but had
been kind of pulled either into; in some cases

01:10:59.880 --> 01:11:00.880
they were saying they were pro Obama but in
most cases they were down in the undecided

01:11:00.880 --> 01:11:01.880
column. She had to do something and somehow
that had to happen. She needed to bring those

01:11:01.880 --> 01:11:02.880
people back home. You know, everybody remembers,
of course, her moment of emotional vulnerability

01:11:02.880 --> 01:11:03.880
in New Hampshire. I think that in fact a big
factor and I also think the people of New

01:11:03.880 --> 01:11:04.880
Hampshire, if you have spent any time there
as I have, there was a very strong sense of

01:11:04.880 --> 01:11:05.880
people in New Hampshire who were very sophisticated
about politics. And the notion that the media

01:11:05.880 --> 01:11:06.880
narrative, which was true, which was that
if Obama had of won New Hampshire, the race

01:11:06.880 --> 01:11:07.880
would basically have been over. I think there
was a backlash to that among a lot of voters

01:11:07.880 --> 01:11:08.880
in New Hampshire, who didn't want the race
to end and didn't want to be part of the coronation

01:11:08.880 --> 01:11:09.880
of a candidate who would have been so untested
at that point. To give Barack Obama - given

01:11:09.880 --> 01:11:10.880
his relatively newer resume, his relatively
brief time on the national stage; to allow

01:11:10.880 --> 01:11:11.880
him to take the Democratic nomination having
only had to succeed in one caucus and one

01:11:11.880 --> 01:11:12.880
primary, I think struck people in a very conscious
way as being a problem. If you look at the

01:11:12.880 --> 01:11:13.880
polls from New Hampshire, one of the things
you will notice is that - and people say,

01:11:13.880 --> 01:11:14.880
"The polls are so wrong, the polls are so
wrong"; they weren't really that wrong. And

01:11:14.880 --> 01:11:15.880
what the polls showed going into election
day, was that Obama had a lead, Hillary had

01:11:15.880 --> 01:11:16.880
 - I won't be able to quote the numbers for
you but Obama had 'x' percent, Hillary had

01:11:16.880 --> 01:11:17.880
'y' percent, and there was a 'z' percent undecided.
Obama basically hit his number; what didn't

01:11:17.880 --> 01:11:18.880
happen on election day was that he didn't
also get any undecided voters. So what you

01:11:18.880 --> 01:11:19.880
saw was something you never see in politics,
which is essentially close to 100% of the

01:11:19.880 --> 01:11:20.880
undecided voters went for Hillary Clinton
and so the polls actually had gotten, I think

01:11:20.880 --> 01:11:21.880
actually got it right in New Hampshire. What
people got wrong was applying the normal predictive

01:11:21.880 --> 01:11:22.880
models to how undecided would break, because
no model ever predicts that a 100% of undecideds

01:11:22.880 --> 01:11:23.880
will all go in one direction. But the combination
of Hillary's moment of vulnerability, Obama's

01:11:23.880 --> 01:11:24.880
moment of nastiness, if you will, at least
ice coldness on the stage when he said you're

01:11:24.880 --> 01:11:25.880
like blowing off Hillary, both contributing
to the same thing which made her seem a much

01:11:25.880 --> 01:11:26.880
more sympathetic and appealing figure, especially
to women voters, and this perception that

01:11:26.880 --> 01:11:27.880
the people of New Hampshire didn't want to
be the place where the race ended. I think

01:11:27.880 --> 01:11:28.880
those were all important factors. And I'd
say on the margin, there was some number of

01:11:28.880 --> 01:11:29.880
independent voters in New Hampshire who, seeing
what they thought was an Obama landslide,

01:11:29.880 --> 01:11:30.880
decided in a strategic voting way that they'd
rather vote for McCain. And it's an open primary

01:11:30.880 --> 01:11:31.880
and independents can vote in either one of
the races. There were a fair number of New

01:11:31.880 --> 01:11:32.880
Hampshirens, I can say empirically, and I
think the data actually shows this, that were

01:11:32.880 --> 01:11:33.880
actually torn and who actually - their favorite
two candidates were Obama and McCain and they

01:11:33.880 --> 01:11:34.880
were very centrist kind of liberal Republicans
 - liberal Conservatives, or very conservative

01:11:34.880 --> 01:11:35.880
Liberals, if you will, who on the day of the
election thought that my votes not going to

01:11:35.880 --> 01:11:36.880
count in the Democratic primary, why not go
the Republican primary and vote for McCain

01:11:36.880 --> 01:11:37.880
where it actually will count because that
race was seen as very tight between him and

01:11:37.880 --> 01:11:38.880
Mitt Romney so some combination of those factors,
I think tell the story there.

01:11:38.880 --> 01:11:39.880
&gt;&gt; It's a good answer and you did answer my
specific question but in particular I was

01:11:39.880 --> 01:11:40.880
referring to the exit polls on the day of
