01:12:02.880 --> 01:12:03.880
of that, you know?

01:12:03.880 --> 01:12:04.880
John Heilemann: Thank you. Well, uh...I think
that the answer to the second question will

01:12:04.880 --> 01:12:05.880
be a little too tendentious for us to get
into right now. But I have read the book you

01:12:05.880 --> 01:12:06.880
are talking about although I have a feeling
that it's written with some [inaudible] of

01:12:06.880 --> 01:12:07.880
ideological predispositions that don't make
it quite straight journalism given the title.

01:12:07.880 --> 01:12:08.880
The answer to the first question is yeah.
I mean, I think that Obama thinks that the

01:12:08.880 --> 01:12:09.880
amount of crises that he faced when he came
in were on a historic level. He, like Hillary

01:12:09.880 --> 01:12:10.880
Clinton, a lot of Presidential aspirants,
really like "Team of Rivals". They think it's

01:12:10.880 --> 01:12:11.880
a really great book. Hillary Clinton tried
to institute a team of rivals on her campaign.

01:12:11.880 --> 01:12:12.880
It doesn't work very well on campaigns it
turns out especially if you're not willing

01:12:12.880 --> 01:12:13.880
to mediate between the war and factions and
then make clear decisions on the basis of

01:12:13.880 --> 01:12:14.880
on this letter, we fight. Her theory was if
you let her fight, the best ideas will come

01:12:14.880 --> 01:12:15.880
to the top. She didn't seem to realize that
when the best ideas came to the top, she needed

01:12:15.880 --> 01:12:16.880
to then endorse one of them and choose that
as a course of action; she seemed to just

01:12:16.880 --> 01:12:17.880
let people kind of fight endlessly. There's
no doubt that Obama had read the book and

01:12:17.880 --> 01:12:18.880
there's also no doubt that he admires Lincoln
a lot. But you know, I - I mean, Hillary Clinton

01:12:18.880 --> 01:12:19.880
was his rival in the Democratic nomination
fight, but I'm being maybe a little bit too

01:12:19.880 --> 01:12:20.880
literal about the title of the book, but if
you look around, I think people naturally

01:12:20.880 --> 01:12:21.880
kind of fastened on to that when he put her
in the Cabinet. I don't think he really thought

01:12:21.880 --> 01:12:22.880
of her that way, in a funny way. I mean, he
obviously did know that he had fought this

01:12:22.880 --> 01:12:23.880
race against her and knew that she had been
his rival but I think he wanted to send-in

01:12:23.880 --> 01:12:24.880
choosing her, he thought she would do a good
job and he wanted to send a message to the

01:12:24.880 --> 01:12:25.880
world about his "bigness", you know, as a
person who was able to move past the campaign

01:12:25.880 --> 01:12:26.880
and pull and put someone in the job that he
thought would do the best in that job, and

01:12:26.880 --> 01:12:27.880
that not only did he want that substantively,
but he wanted to be seen as someone who would

01:12:27.880 --> 01:12:28.880
do that. You know, if you look at the makeup
of his cabinet in general, there's not a lot

01:12:28.880 --> 01:12:29.880
of rivalry there. I mean, there are a lot
of people who Obama was very friendly with

01:12:29.880 --> 01:12:30.880
or very close to in the past. People like
Arnie Duncan, the Education Secretary, who

01:12:30.880 --> 01:12:31.880
he had a great relationship with. In the White
House, the same two of the three people that

01:12:31.880 --> 01:12:32.880
Obama actually listens to, who he'd listened
to during the campaign and continues to listen

01:12:32.880 --> 01:12:33.880
to, Robert Gibbs and David Axelrod are still
there. He swapped out David Plouffe for Rahm

01:12:33.880 --> 01:12:34.880
Emanuel but again it's a very tight circle
of people within the White House who Obama

01:12:34.880 --> 01:12:35.880
actually cares about their opinions. And you
know in the context of foreign policy, you

01:12:35.880 --> 01:12:36.880
know again this a hard thing again for many
of Obama's more progressive backers to swallow

01:12:36.880 --> 01:12:37.880
but I think you know there was consistency.
Hillary Clinton, Bob Gates, Jim Jones; all

01:12:37.880 --> 01:12:38.880
pretty hawkish for Democrats. I mean, in Gates's
case, not really a Democratic. People who

01:12:38.880 --> 01:12:39.880
were much to the right of where I think a
lot of progressive voters were in terms of

01:12:39.880 --> 01:12:40.880
foreign policy, but that's not a team of rivals,
that's a team of people who believe what Barack

01:12:40.880 --> 01:12:41.880
Obama seems to believe about foreign policy.

01:12:41.880 --> 01:12:42.880
Again, I say many progressives don't, we don't
want to believe that but I think everything

01:12:42.880 --> 01:12:43.880
that's happened over the course of the first
year, particularly surrounding the decisions

01:12:43.880 --> 01:12:44.880
in Afghanistan, suggest that those people
were put in the office because they had the

01:12:44.880 --> 01:12:45.880
same orientation towards national security
that Obama actually has. I mean, I'll conclude

01:12:45.880 --> 01:12:46.880
by saying it is, I think, one of the biggest
problems for Obama, is the Rorschach Blot,

01:12:46.880 --> 01:12:47.880
blankness of his campaign and the amount of
projection that people put on him and believe

01:12:47.880 --> 01:12:48.880
things that he never was, and I think one
of things most, where it's most striking,

01:12:48.880 --> 01:12:49.880
is in this area; because I think foreign policy
in the end may be the thing that will be determinative

01:12:49.880 --> 01:12:50.880
in the 2012 elections. Around the time in
2011, he has to decide whether or not to withdraw

01:12:50.880 --> 01:12:51.880
troops from Afghanistan as he said he was
going to. You know, a lot of people on the

01:12:51.880 --> 01:12:52.880
left heard Obama's speech about the Iraq War
in 2002 and thought he said he was against

01:12:52.880 --> 01:12:53.880
the Iraq War and that he was an anti-war person,
and what he said was, "I'm not against all

01:12:53.880 --> 01:12:54.880
wars, I'm against dumb wars", and I think
it's a salutary and important thing for people

01:12:54.880 --> 01:12:55.880
who, to listen to both parts of that sentence.
Again, I take no position on the subject but

01:12:55.880 --> 01:12:56.880
this is not a guy who is a pacifist, and I
think his appointments in foreign policy demonstrate

01:12:56.880 --> 01:12:57.880
that's pretty clearly the case. So anyway,
thank you very much, you guys, for coming.

01:12:57.880 --> 01:12:57.881
[applause]

